Definition doesn't match but subject type does. The object represents the actual minimum value of the measured variable, whereas the subject represents the minimum permissible value, which may in fact differ from the actual minimum value.

Definitions match but subject type is narrower. An exact match between the subject and object is formed when the subjects's "function" attribute (/element(*,PhysicalType)/distribution/online/url/@function) has a value of "download". See: https://eml.ecoinformatics.org/schema/eml-resource_xsd.html#OnlineType_url

No match can be found.  There is no single field that lists the format type for a data object in the EML standard. This value can be estimated by sending the EML objectName value to a MIME type guessing algorithm.

Definitions match but object type is broader.  Requires logic to determine if the upper and lower bounds match to form a single value. Unequal object values will not be averaged since this would modify the information.  Note, it appears the subject assumes the spatial reference system "WGS 84" and is therefore unclear if this requirement is met by EML. For this reason the match type is given a low confidence.

Definitions match but object type is narrower.  An exact match may be formed during implementation by the concatenation of the subject's sub properties in the order: cov:southBoundingCoordinate cov:westBoundingCoordinate cov:northBoundingCoordinate cov:eastBoundingCoordinate with a blank space separator.

Definitions match but subject type is broader. The subject definition recommends a format, but does not enforce it. Therefore an ideal solution is an algorithm capable of identifying probable formats and converting them to the object.  Assuming the subject's recommended format, conversion entails reversing the order of lon/lat values to lat/lon, replacing comma delimiters with spaces, and ensuring the first and final points are identical.
